(73120, 180219, 0, 1, 'Lucky star', '', '2013-01-01 00:00:00', 2000, 19, 1, 1, '曾經留連路口 只為追逐一陣風\nDon''t ask me how it worth or the price.\nI did it cause I know the reason why. \n強迫自己勇敢 冷潮熱諷都吞過\nThis life is the movie of mine.\nI gonna do more something untill die.\n有時迷惘 該獨自向前嗎\n總覺得有些話不知該對誰講\n我不是驕傲 只是有嚮往的地方\n\n直到遇見你們 我才敢闖\n不說多餘的話 了解我想法\n就算會有軟弱的時候\n總會有能夠依靠的肩膀\n我不夠完美\n但在你們身上我找到 孕育夢想的土壤\nMaybe it''s the plan of the Father God.\nYou are my lucky stars！\n\n每張陌生臉孔 隱藏了幾分的夢？\nA new place, a Dream Space！\n眼前的人走過 能多做幾步停留？\none more step, one more chance！\n儘管張狂 像脫韁的野馬 \n有伯樂就不怕有烏雲阻擋\n讓時間淘汰 選擇沉默的傻瓜\n\nAlmighty Lord.\nPlease purify my soul.\nShow me the light! Guide me the road!\nEliminate serpents in jungle!\nYou will control！ You will control！\n\n傷痕,快樂,都是過程\n我用旋律紀錄青春\n有些悸動只有走過的人才懂\n不怕今後各奔東西\n只要記得這一刻\n一首歌 就是永恆', '', 311, '', '', '', '', '緊急巴士  ', '', 0, 1, 1, '2014-03-06 08:45:07', '2014-04-07 17:07:38', '2014-04-07 17:07:38'),
(73121, 180219, 0, 1, '再會', '', '2013-01-01 00:00:00', 2000, 19, 1, 1, '浪費了太多時間 置妳的綿情意愛  妳對我其實無暸解\n免探聽我的行蹤 我欲行自己的路  想瑕多攏總無路用\n天頂的星照置阮的眼前 我已經準備重生\n我欲來走找著我的未來 妳也要保重\n\n心肝有多少無奈猶原欲來說出一聲 再會 無緣的情愛\n心肝有多少感慨猶原欲來說出一聲 再會 過去的目屎\n心肝有多少不捨 外多悲哀 猶原不能阻礙 我的未來\n\n咖啡色彼卡皮箱 裡面裝著我的理想 也裝著幾件的寂寞\n阮汕著異鄉的風 阮的旅途稍微傯倥 懷念著單純的快樂\n\n\n甘說時間的腳步 袂當還我過去的笑容\n追求成功這條路 到底是對 抑是錯誤\n目屎擱卡鹹 阮也吞落腹 現在我欲來出帆\n', '', 312, '', '', '', '', '緊急巴士  ', '', 0, 1, 1, '2014-03-06 08:46:57', '2014-04-07 17:07:41', '2014-04-07 17:07:41'),
(73122, 180219, 0, 1, '彩色的花', '', '2013-01-01 00:00:00', 2000, 19, 1, 1, '你怎會憂頭結面?\n不通擱講過去的事情\n來向前看 來認真衝\n來寫屬於你咱的歌詩\n \n別在那看貓沒點\n恁爸是不屑跟你計較\n為自己的人生負責\n甘還要我來教?\n \n \n彩色的花 開在你咱的心中\n彼是咱的路 \n誰人來阻擋 攏袂通來影響\n彼是咱的路\n \n世事總是來來去去\n甚麼是咱一生的依靠?\n甘願放棄生命 賭上阮青春\n \n眼前的路坎坷難行\n不用煩惱 咱總會有盼望\n花蕊猶原清香\n \n \n做你來笑我憨\n就算你來挑撥\n花開在心中\n阮永遠堅強\n \n \n我的朋友啊 我看到你的血汗\n我的朋友啊 目屎給擦乎乾', '', 245, '', '', '', '', '緊急巴士  ', '', 0, 1, 1, '2014-03-06 08:47:56', '2014-04-07 17:07:44', '2014-04-07 17:07:44'),
(73123, 1892, 6411, 6, 'Wedding 婚禮', '即興吟唱：雲力思  \n編曲：Wolfgang Obrecht\nVocal performance: Inka Mbing\nArranged by Wolfgang Obrecht\n\n百年前來到印度的湖北人，以鑲牙的手藝存活，轉業為合格牙醫後，散居印度各地執業，是印度華人中最能融入印度社會的一群。中文對他們來說，已是陌生的語言，但他們仍謹守祭祖古禮。一場印度湖北人的婚慶，傳統跪拜祭祖後，鄉親移至教堂觀禮，晩上接著圓桌宴客，以寶萊塢歌舞佐客家菜。雲力思想像著他們多重的身份，以即興吟唱書寫世居印度的湖北人的故事。\n\nAt a Hubei Chinese wedding in India, one finds a melding of various traditions. It begins with the familiar Chinese rituals, where relatives gather to pray to the family ancestors. The families then convene at a church for a Christian wedding ceremony. Then the scene returns to a Chinese-style wedding banquet, complete with round tables and a feast of many courses. One especially unique feature of the Hubei Chinese weddings in India: revelers sing and dance to Bollywood songs while eating Hakkanese food. With such a fusion in mind, Taiwanese Atayal singer Inka Mbing improvised this vocal melody.\n \n(Chinese from Hubei Province started to come to India over a century ago, and many in the first wave of these migrants took up folk dentistry (in the Chinese tradition) as their main trade. Eventually younger generations of Hubei Chinese in India trained to become Western medical dentists, which for the Indian Chinese has been the most promising path for integrating into Indian society.) \n', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 2014, 25, 0, 7, '', '', 148, '', '', '', '鍾適芳', '大大樹音樂圖像', '', 1, 1, 0, '2014-03-06 16:18:49', '2015-03-12 14:05:36', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(73124, 1892, 6411, 10, 'Train to Unknown 開往未知的火車', '音景：2013 阿薩姆省Guwahati車站、 2013 Ballygunge社區獨立紀念日遊行廣播\nSoundscape: Guwahati Train Station, Assam, 2013; Song from a march commemorating Indian Independence in the Ballygunge District, 2013.\n\n\n1962年夜裡的敲門聲，驚醒了無數世居印度的華人。旅途上的未知與恐懼，藏在記憶最底處，不願被翻攪。歷史沒有留下證據，我們以動畫及音樂，述說從印度東北到拉加斯坦邦迪奧里集中營，七日七夜旅途上的心理。\nIn 1962, a border dispute at the Himalayan border broke out into a war between India. Soon after that, Chinese residents across India started to receive surprise late-night visits from the police. They were being summoned to pack their belongings, leave their homes and board a train to a destination unknown. They were not told where they were being taken to an internment camp in Rajasthan. To date, there are very few recorded historical accounts of this event. In "From Border to Border," we used animation segments and music to convey the story of a grueling journey that lasted seven days and seven nights to Deoli, Rajasthan, as told to us by a group of Indian Chinese internees. \n\n\n歌曲錄自印度獨立紀念日遊行廣播，Ae Mere Watan Ke Logon（祖國的人民），為紀念1962中印邊界戰爭犧牲的軍人而作，至今仍是膾炙人口的愛國歌曲。\nThe song in this segment, "Ae Mere Watan Ke Logon" ("O! The People of My Country"), was written to commemorate the Indian soldiers who died during the Sino-Indian War of 1962, and remains a patriotic song in India today.   \n', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 2014, 25, 0, 7, '', '', 179, '', '', '', '鍾適芳', '大大樹音樂圖像', '', 1, 1, 0, '2014-03-06 16:19:53', '2015-03-12 14:05:36', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(73125, 1892, 6411, 11, 'A Dance for Neem Trees 為苦楝樹而舞', '曲、手風琴：Wolfgang Obrecht\n琵琶：鍾玉鳳\n電吉他：大竹研\n12弦木吉他：David Chen \nWritten and performed on accordion by Wolfgang Obrecht\nPipa: Chung Yufeng\nElectric Guitar: Ken Ohtake\n12-string acoustic guitar: David Chen\n\n\n\n透過印度華人的口述歷史，我們認識了這棵樹。沙漠中的苦楝樹，是集中營裡最簡單的希望。\nWhile collecting oral history for production of "From Border to Border," we became acquainted with India''s ubiquitous Neem tree, the only visible sign of hope at the internment camps.  \n', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 2014, 25, 0, 7, '', '', 433, '', 'Wolfgang Obrecht', '', '鍾適芳', '大大樹音樂圖像', '', 1, 1, 0, '2014-03-06 16:20:22', '2015-03-12 14:05:36', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(73126, 1892, 6411, 15, 'Jana Gana Mana  (Thou Art the Ruler of the Minds of All People ) 人民的意志', '曲：泰戈爾\n演奏：鍾玉鳳（琵琶）、大竹研（電吉他）\nMusic by Rabindranath Tagore\nPerformed by Chung Yufeng (Pipa) and Ken Ohtake (Electric Guitar)\n\n紀錄片拍攝的城市加爾各答，是西孟加拉邦的首都，當地的語言是孟加拉文，泰戈爾寫作的語文。這裡也曾是英屬印度的首都、反殖知識份子熱烈聚集的所在。西孟加拉邦因此有著不滅的文學、民歌、知識份子論政的燭火。「人民的意志」原為泰戈爾的詩作，後來被選為印度國歌。\n\n\nWe filmed "From Border to Border" in Kolkata, the capital city of West Bengal in India. The local language is Bengali, the language of renowned Indian writer and Nobel laureate Rabindranath Tagore, who composed the song. Kolkata was also the capital during the British occupation, when the city was known as "Calcutta," and thus was the center of a passionate anti-colonialist movement. West Bengali thus has a long tradition of dissident literature, folk music and intellectual thought. "Jana Gana Mana," was originally a poem written by Tagore eventually became adapted for India''s national anthem, which Chung Yufeng and Ken Ohtake have in turn adapted into an instrumental piece.   \n', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 2014, 25, 0, 7, '', '', 217, '', '泰戈爾 Rabindranath Tagore', '', '鍾適芳', '大大樹音樂圖像', '', 1, 1, 0, '2014-03-06 16:20:31', '2015-03-12 14:05:36', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(73127, 1892, 6411, 16, 'CIty of Night 夜之城', '曲：鍾玉鳳、David Chen\n詞、演唱、編曲、吉他：David Chen\n手風琴：Wolfgang Obrecht\nMusic by Chung Yufeng, David Chen\nLyrics and arrangement by David Chen\nAcoustic Guitar and Vocal: David Chen\nAccordion: Wolfgang Obrecht\n\n\n從一開始，我們就試著為這影片找一首屬於加爾各答歌詩，一種時代的、孤自的吟唱，直到David Chen隨著玉鳳寫的主題旋律，哼唱出我們尋覓已久的故事：他從孟買出生的英國作家Rudyard Kipling一部描寫加爾各答的小說中獲得靈感，用想像創造了1930年代胡格利河（Hoogly River）碼頭的情景與聲響，儘管整篇原作流露著傲慢與輕蔑（Kipling是毫無歉疚的大英帝國支持者，他引用一首維多利亞時代詩歌對「倫敦」的比喻，將加爾各答喻為「惡夜之城」），但David Chen巧妙轉移了敘事觀點，唱出了大時代下移民者悲涼而孤寂的生命經驗，就像透過Mrinal Sen電影，我們在山東綢小販王魯身上，聽見被時代遺忘的聲音。\n\nFrom the start of production, we looked for a song with lyrics about Kolkata, one that could reflect the times and the feeling of isolation experienced by Chinese migrants to India. A collaboration between David Chen and Chung Yufeng produced what we were looking for: David wrote lyrics to Yufeng''s melody, drawing from Bombay-born Rudyard Kipling''s writings on Calcutta to create scenes that bring to mind the Hoogly River and wharf areas of Kolkata in the 1930s. Although a tone of condescending disdain runs throughout Kipling''s work (He was an unapologetic supporter of the British Empire and dubbed Calcutta "The City of Dreadful Night," invoking a bleak Victorian poem about London), David found a mood that speaks to the desolate experience of a migrant. He shifted the narrator''s perspective to lend a voice to a normally-silenced character, just as Wang Lu, the Chinese silk peddler, is granted a voice in Mrinal Sen''s aforementioned film.  \n', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 2014, 25, 0, 7, 'I was born by the river  生在河畔\nThis river, my home  河就是我家\nWhere the sailors, they drink, they yell and they roar  水手們在那買醉、哭喊，也咆哮\n\nThey sing of love,  他們為愛\nof sorrow, of war    為悲、為戰爭而歌\nThey sing of their dreams, of a home on another shore  他們為逐夢、為彼岸的家而歌\n\nIf I leave this home  一旦我離開家\nWill I see it again?   還會再見嗎？\n\nThis city of night   這夜之城\nWhere the lights are low? 當夜燈低垂\n\nThis city of dread  這恐懼之城\nI have no place to go 我無處可逃\n\nIf I leave this home  一旦我離開家\nWill I see it again?   還會再見嗎？', '', 201, '', 'David Chen, 鍾玉鳳', 'David Chen', '鍾適芳', '大大樹音樂圖像', '', 1, 1, 0, '2014-03-06 16:21:52', '2015-03-12 14:05:36', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(73128, 1892, 6411, 18, 'Borderless 無國界', '曲、手風琴、演唱：Wolfgang Obrecht\n琵琶、演唱：鍾玉鳳\n12絃木吉他、演唱：David Chen\n電吉他：大竹研\nWritten and performed by Wolfgang Obrecht on accordion and vocals\nPipa, vocals: Chung Yufeng\n12-string acoustic guitar, vocals: David Chen\nElectric Guitar: Ken Ohtake\n\n\nWolfgang Obrecht為路上跨越語言、文化界限的經驗而寫。\nIn light of encountering an unfamiliar language and culture, Wolfgang drew from his experiences in "crossing a border," including his time in India, to compose this piece.\n', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 2014, 25, 0, 7, '', '', 469, '', 'Wolfgang Obrecht', '', '鍾適芳', '大大樹音樂圖像', '', 1, 1, 0, '2014-03-06 16:22:19', '2015-03-12 14:05:36', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
